    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="962"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d962">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 European War 1939/425: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-09">August 9,
                            1941</date>.<lb/>[Received August 9—1:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1458. The following third person note has been received from the People’s
                    Commissariat for Foreign Affairs.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“The People’s Commissariat for Foreign Affairs of the USSR presents its
                        compliments to the Embassy of the United States of America and has the honor
                        to state that in the present war with Germany which has been forced upon the
                        Soviet Union the Government of the Union of SSR will observe the universally
                        known international treaties concerning the rules of warfare and in
                        particular, (1) the Hague Convention of October 1907 regarding the rules and
                        customs of warfare on land<note n="45" xml:id="d962fn45">Signed at The Hague
                            on October 18, 1907; for text, see <ref target="frus1907p2#pg_1204">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1907, pt. 2, p.
                            1204</ref>; or 36 Stat. 2277.</note> and, (2) the Geneva Protocol of
                        July [<hi rend="italic">June</hi>] 17, 1925 prohibiting the use in war of
                        suffocating, poisonous or other similar gases as well as of bacteriological
                            means,<note n="46" xml:id="d962fn46">For text, see <ref
                                target="frus1925v01#pg_89">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 89</ref>; or League of Nations
                            Treaty Series, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xciv</hi>, p. 65.</note> (3)
                        the Geneva Convention of July 27, 1928 [<hi rend="italic">1929</hi>]
                        regarding improvement of the care for the wounded and sick in fighting
                            armies<note n="47" xml:id="d962fn47">For text, see <ref
                                target="frus1929v01#pg_321">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1929, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 321</ref>; or League of Nations
                            Treaty Series, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">cxviii</hi>, p. 303.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p>The Soviet Government considers it however necessary to state that in view of
                        the systematic violation by Hitlerite Germany of international <pb
                            facs="1018" n="1006" xml:id="pg_1006"/> agreements and conventions the
                        Soviet Government shall observe with respect to Germany the above mentioned
                        treaties and conventions only insofar as they are observed by Germany.
                        Moscow, August 8, 1941.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
